    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Schools Aren't Pawns</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Assemblyman Scott Stringer letter scores Mayor Rudolph W Giuliani for delaying start of school construction projects pending action by state to raise New York City's debt limit</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani is delaying the start of more than 80 construction projects pending action in Albany to raise New York City's debt limit (news article, May 25).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani is delaying the start of more than 80 construction projects pending action in Albany to raise New York City's debt limit (news article, May 25).</p>
        <p>Putting aside the question of whether or not the city's debt limit should be increased, it is unconscionable that the freeze has been extended to the city school system. The city plans to construct buildings that will allow 58,000 more children to attend schools with real classrooms that are not former closets or bathrooms.</p>
        <p>If the mayor wants to gain leverage in negotiations by delaying construction projects, he should halt frivolous projects like the construction of a new minor league baseball stadium in Staten Island instead of using our children as pawns in complex negotiations.</p>
        <p>SCOTT STRINGER  Assemblyman, 67th Dist.  Albany, May 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
